<h1 id="intro-to-audification-and-sonification">Intro To Audification and Sonification</h1>
<p>Welcome! This is my first introduction to a variety of tools and ideas. I first learned about the concepts of Audification and Sonification from a great friend's work while I was in college and the ideas have been inspiring me recently so I decided to dive in and do a bit of exploring.</p>
<p>The examples I give will be pretty basic and the field has been around for a number of years, but is not nearly as developed as visual aids for data analysis. The reasons to consider using audification and sonification is that you have an immensely powerful auditory system capable of great feats in pattern recognition. This introductory post won't go into much of how it all works or even great examples where your auditory system may identify components that a simple visual aid does not easily distinguish, but look forward to future posts on those topics.</p>
<p>I have set all of this up in python, which is new for me as well, but has been a great experience thus far. If you have questions or comments about my setup, feel free to reach out!</p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id="background">Background</h2>
<h3 id="audification">Audification</h3>
<p>From Wikipedia: Audification is an auditory display technique for representing a sequence of data values as sound. An audification does this by interpreting the data sequence, usually a time series, as an audio waveform: input data is mapped to sound pressure levels.</p>
<p>In short, it is just a way to listen directly to the data without applying any further processing or modification. It works particularly well with large data sets that may translate well to sime series information.</p>
<h3 id="sonification">Sonification</h3>
<p>From Wikipedia: Sonification is the use of non-speech audio to convey information or perceptualize data.[1] Auditory perception has advantages in temporal, spatial, amplitude, and frequency resolution that open possibilities as an alternative or complement to visualization techniques.</p>
<p>Potentially less clear when reading this definition, but involves mapping the data to a sonic parameter. In our case, we will map data to the frequency of a sine wave, but it could be mapped to amplitude or the frequency of a filter, etc...</p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id="lets-dive-in">Let's Dive In</h2>
<p>We will dive into a basic example taking the S&amp;P500 index of the past 115 years and attempting to listen to it. I don't expect this example will lead us to many new insights about the data, but I hope it will outline the infrastructure to get up and running and later posts can play with some data that might be more interesting sonically.</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><br></p>
<h3 id="audification">Audification</h3>
<p>This is the process of listening to the data directly, the only processing we do will be conversion between different formats (structure and scale). The end result will still be a isomorphic representation of the data we started with.</p>
<p>In order to convert this audio to a wave file, we first need to convert it from a pandas dataframe to a numpy array in the format that the IPython.display.Audio class will expect.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h4 id="daily-returns-audification">Daily Returns Audification</h4>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[133]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight"><pre><span class="c"># Transpose and convert to numpy array</span>
<span class="n">returns_numpy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">returns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">T</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">as_matrix</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c"># slice array</span>
<span class="n">returns_numpy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">returns_numpy</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,:]</span>
<span class="n">returns_numpy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nan_to_num</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">returns_numpy</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">returns_numpy</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[133]:</div>


<div class="output_text output_subarea output_pyout">
<pre>
array([ 0.        ,  0.01134002,  0.00473654, ..., -0.00030332,
        0.00275494, -0.00076608])
</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[134]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight"><pre><span class="c"># Normalize array</span>
<span class="c"># - convert the scale of the data to range from [-1,1]. To do so,</span>
<span class="c"># we will divide the array by the max value of the array.</span>

<span class="c"># find max</span>
<span class="n">myMax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">returns_numpy</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c"># find min</span>
<span class="n">myMin</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">min</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">returns_numpy</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c"># if negative, convert to positive for comparison</span>
<span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">myMin</span> <span class="o">&lt;</span> <span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">myMin</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">myMin</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span>


<span class="c"># save larger of abs(max and min)</span>
<span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">myMax</span> <span class="o">&gt;=</span> <span class="n">myMin</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">absMax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">myMax</span>
<span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">absMax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">myMin</span>

<span class="c"># divide numpy array by max value</span>
<span class="n">returns_numpy</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">returns_numpy</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">absMax</span>
<span class="n">returns_numpy</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[134]:</div>


<div class="output_text output_subarea output_pyout">
<pre>
array([ 0.        ,  0.04952034,  0.02068383, ..., -0.00132456,
        0.01203045, -0.00334535])
</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[135]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight"><pre><span class="c"># Let us plot it to be sure that it is accurate to what we saw</span>
<span class="c"># above and we have modified the y-axis scale to a max value of 1.</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">returns_numpy</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><br></p>
<h4 id="analysis">Analysis</h4>
<p>You can pick up on the large fluctuations in return values and it would be interesting to line them up with the timeline of the market prices to better understand how they fit together.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>need to add time values so I can plot both on same axis</p></li>
<li><p>for SONIFICATION, change the frequency scaling to be done over log of that range. why? human hearing.</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><br></p>
<h3 id="sonification">Sonification</h3>
<p>This is the process of listening to the data after it has been mapped to a parameter of an audio generator or audio filter. We will utilize the files we had already processed from DataFrames into normalized NumPy arrays to begin.</p>
<p>Our goal is to convert these two arrays to the frequency of a sine wave.</p>
<p>I am adding a helper functions that will be used in later sections. More details on them can be found:</p>
<ul>
<li>http://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/37376-oscillator-and-signal-generator/content/oscillator.m</li>
<li>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instantaneous_phase#Instantaneous_frequency</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<h4 id="helper-function">Helper Function</h4>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[140]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight"><pre><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">fm_signal_generator</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq_vector</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">duration</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">phase</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fs</span><span class="p">):</span>
    
    <span class="c"># create numpy array for all time values</span>
    <span class="n">t</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">linspace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">duration</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fs</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">duration</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c"># use the center of the requested frequencies as the carrier frequency:</span>
    <span class="n">carrier</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">min</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq_vector</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq_vector</span><span class="p">)])</span>
    
    <span class="c"># determine normalized max frequency</span>
    <span class="n">norm_maxfreq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">((</span><span class="nb">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq_vector</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">carrier</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">fs</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="mi">2</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pi</span>
    
    <span class="c"># normalize the freq range from -1 to 1</span>
    <span class="n">freq_normalized</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">freq_vector</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="nb">min</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq_vector</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">freq_normalized</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">freq_vector</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="nb">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq_vector</span><span class="p">))</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
    
    <span class="c"># generate fm signal:</span>
    <span class="n">wave</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sin</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pi</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">carrier</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">t</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">norm_maxfreq</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">cumsum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq_normalized</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pi</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">phase</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="c"># normalize wave to +/- 1</span>
    <span class="n">wave</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">wave</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="nb">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">wave</span><span class="p">))</span>
    
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">wave</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><br></p>
<h4 id="setting-sonification-parameters">Setting Sonification Parameters</h4>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[116]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight"><pre><span class="c"># set duration of desired playback (seconds)</span>
<span class="n">duration</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">5</span>

<span class="c"># set framerate based on number of points</span>
<span class="n">fs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">44100</span>

<span class="n">phase</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>


<span class="c"># Resampled the data to fit the desired time length</span>
<span class="n">adj_close_numpy_resampled</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">signal</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fs</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">duration</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy_resampled</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[141]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class="highlight"><pre><span class="c"># Rescale data to fall between desired auditory range</span>

<span class="c"># define current and new range</span>
<span class="n">cur_max</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy_resampled</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">cur_min</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">min</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy_resampled</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">n_max</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1500</span>
<span class="n">n_min</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">100</span>

<span class="c"># define scaled array over length of data</span>
<span class="n">adj_close_numpy_scaled</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">zeros</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy_resampled</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c"># modify all values</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy_resampled</span><span class="p">)):</span>
    
    <span class="n">adj_close_numpy_scaled</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_max</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">n_min</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">cur_max</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">cur_min</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy_resampled</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">cur_min</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">n_min</span>
    
    

<span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">adj_close_numpy_scaled</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<h2 id="conclusions">Conclusions</h2>
<p>Overall, a successful introduction <em>(I like to think)</em>. Doing audification and/or sonification may provide you with some insights into the data not immediately apparent in a basic plot. It may give you insights on how to filter the data or other clues to dive into the data.</p>
<p>If you are like me, this process has probably led to more questions about what to do, what works, best practices, and many of the foundational aspects about how to set parameters for you to best identify information about the data. Unfortunately, I don't have all of those answers either, but explore and check out my other posts as well.</p>
<p>If you have any comments or questions, feel free to reach out to me on email, twitter, facebook, and the like to have more discussion. I might not have all of the answers, but I am happy to discuss!</p>
